{"key":"processedPost-12304846","value":{"id":12304846,"first":12304432,"last":12304873,"when":1270055790,"utime":"03/31/10 08:16 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>PsilliCoder said:</b><br />Any comments about this thread:<br /><br /><a href=\"/forums/showflat.php/Number/6356064#6356064\" class=\"pp\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.shroomery.org/forums/<wbr>showflat.php/Number/6356064#63560<wbr>64</a><br /></blockquote><br /><br />I strongly disagree with my old friend.&nbsp; Properly pasteurized straw is not prone to contamination.&nbsp; In addition, cased straw is MORE prone to contamination.&nbsp; I'm not new to this.&nbsp; I have bales of straw stacked all the way to the roof of my barn.&nbsp; I buy it by the semi-truck load, as well as buying over 1000 pounds of rye berries per month.&nbsp; Straw IS a one flush wonder.&nbsp; That's why it's so beneficial.&nbsp; You get your product in one flush rather than waiting for several flushes.&nbsp; This is far more efficient.&nbsp; You get one flush and then have a second substrate colonized and waiting to take its place.<br /><br />You 'can' get more than one flush from straw, but my preference is to put the spent straw logs outdoors in a shady spot and let them flush there.&nbsp; This clears out fruiting room real estate for a new straw substrate, making the most of available space.<br />RR","title":"Re: Straw: To case or not to case"}}